+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013cZPBzs7mXhRBEZeA5g7hs","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now let me provide you with a comprehensive summary of the project:\n\n## Comprehensive Task Queue Project Overview\n\n### Directory Structure\n\n```\n/workspace/\n├── .eslintrc.cjs                 # ESLint configuration\n├── .gitignore\n├── .thunderdome/                 # Benchmarking/testing framework\n│   └── rubric.yaml\n├── TASK.md                       # Main project overview\n├── package.json                  # Project dependencies and scripts\n├── tsconfig.json                 # TypeScript configuration\n├── vitest.config.ts             # Vitest test runner configuration\n├── phases/                       # 12 phase requirements\n│   ├── phase-01.md\n│   ├── phase-02.md\n│   ├── phase-03.md\n│   ├── phase-04.md\n│   ├── phase-05.md\n│   ├── phase-06.md\n│   ├── phase-07.md\n│   ├── phase-08.md\n│   ├── phase-09.md\n│   ├── phase-10.md\n│   ├── phase-11.md\n│   └── phase-12.md\n├── src/                          # Implementation directory (empty, contains only .gitkeep)\n└── dist/                         # Will be compiled output\n```\n\n---\n\n## All Phase Files - COMPLETE CONTENTS\n\n### Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-01.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n\nImplement the core of the task queue: the ability to add tasks and retrieve them in first-in, first-out order.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- The queue should accept a payload (any data) when a task is added, and return a task object.\n- Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\n- New tasks start in a \"pending\" state.\n- Retrieving the next task should return the oldest pending task and transition it to a \"processing\" state.\n- If no tasks are available, retrieval should return `null`.\n- There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\n```\n\n### Phase 2: Named Queues\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-02.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 2: Named Queues\n\nExtend the system to support multiple independent queues, each identified by a name.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks are added to a specific named queue. If no name is given, a default queue is used.\n- Each named queue operates independently -- adding to one does not affect another.\n- Retrieving a task pulls from the specified queue only.\n- Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\n- There should be a way to list all queue names that exist.\n- Asking for a task from a non-existent or empty queue returns `null`.\n- The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\n```\n\n### Phase 3: Priority\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-03.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 3: Priority\n\nAdd priority support so that more urgent tasks are processed before less urgent ones.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks can be assigned a priority level from 1 (highest) to 10 (lowest). The default priority is 5.\n- When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\n- Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\n- Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\n- Priority operates per-queue -- each named queue maintains its own priority ordering.\n- The task object should expose its priority level.\n```\n\n### Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-04.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to defer tasks so they only become available for processing after a specified time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A task can be given a delay (in milliseconds) or a specific future time at which it becomes available.\n- Delayed tasks are added to the queue immediately but are not returned when retrieving until their availability time has passed.\n- Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\n- When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\n- The task object should indicate when it becomes available.\n- Delays work correctly with named queues.\n```\n\n### Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-05.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n\nAdd automatic retry functionality so that failed tasks can be re-attempted with increasing delays.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- There should be a way to mark a processing task as completed or failed.\n- When a task fails and has retries remaining, it is automatically re-added to the queue with a delay.\n- The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\n- The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\n- The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\n- The task should track how many times it has been attempted.\n- Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\n- If all retries are exhausted, the task remains in a failed state.\n```\n\n### Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-06.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n\nAdd a dead letter queue (DLQ) to capture tasks that have permanently failed after exhausting all retries.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When a task has no more retries left, it is automatically moved to a dead letter queue associated with its original queue.\n- There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\n- Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\n- It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\n- There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\n- Each named queue has its own independent dead letter queue.\n```\n\n### Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-07.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n\nAdd the ability for tasks to declare dependencies on other tasks, so they only become available once their prerequisites are done.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When adding a task, you can specify a list of task IDs that must complete before this task becomes available.\n- A task with unresolved dependencies is blocked and will not be returned when retrieving.\n- When a dependency completes, the system should check whether any blocked tasks are now unblocked.\n- Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\n- Depending on a non-existent task should cause an error.\n- A failed dependency does NOT automatically fail its dependents -- they remain blocked.\n- There should be a way to inspect a task's dependency status.\n```\n\n### Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-08.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n\nAdd per-queue limits on how many tasks can be processed at the same time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Each queue can have a maximum concurrency setting that limits how many tasks can be in a processing state simultaneously.\n- If the concurrency limit is reached, retrieving a task returns `null` even if pending tasks are available.\n- Completing or failing a task frees up a concurrency slot.\n- By default, queues have no concurrency limit (unlimited).\n- There should be a way to set and query the concurrency limit and current active count for a queue.\n- Concurrency interacts correctly with priority ordering -- the highest-priority available task is still chosen, subject to the concurrency limit.\n```\n\n### Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-09.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n\nAdd the ability to report progress on running tasks and to cancel tasks.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A processing task can report its progress as a percentage (0-100) with an optional message.\n- There should be a way to query a task's current progress.\n- Listeners can subscribe to progress updates for a task and receive notifications when progress changes.\n- Subscriptions should be cancellable (unsubscribe).\n- Tasks in pending or processing state can be cancelled.\n- Cancelled pending tasks are removed from the queue and will not be returned.\n- Cancelled processing tasks have their status updated accordingly.\n- Cancelled tasks are never retried, even if they had retries remaining.\n```\n\n### Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-10.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to schedule tasks that recur on a regular interval using simple cron-like expressions.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A schedule associates a cron expression with a queue and a task template (the payload to use each time).\n- Support a simple subset of cron expressions:\n  - `*/N * * * *` -- every N minutes\n  - `0 * * * *` -- every hour on the hour\n  - `0 0 * * *` -- every day at midnight\n- There should be a way to create, remove, and list active schedules.\n- A manual \"tick\" or \"check\" mechanism should evaluate all active schedules and enqueue tasks for any that are due. This is used for testing.\n- Once enqueued, recurring tasks are regular tasks subject to all other queue rules.\n- Removing a schedule stops future occurrences from being created.\n```\n\n### Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-11.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n\nAdd a middleware system that can intercept and transform tasks as they are processed.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Middleware functions can be registered per queue.\n- When a task is processed, it passes through all registered middleware in order before reaching the final handler.\n- Each middleware receives the task and a \"next\" function. Calling \"next\" passes control to the next middleware (or the handler).\n- If a middleware does NOT call \"next\", the task processing is skipped.\n- Middleware can modify the task (e.g., adding metadata or transforming the payload).\n- If a middleware throws an error, the task should be marked as failed.\n- A processing function/handler can be registered per queue. It is invoked after all middleware have run.\n- Each queue has its own independent middleware stack.\n```\n\n### Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-12.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n\nAdd the ability to shut down the task queue system in an orderly fashion.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A shutdown operation should signal the system to stop accepting new tasks.\n- After shutdown is initiated, attempting to add new tasks should produce an error.\n- The shutdown should wait for all currently-processing tasks to finish, up to a configurable timeout.\n- If processing tasks do not complete within the timeout, they should be force-cancelled.\n- Callbacks can be registered to run during the shutdown process.\n- The shutdown should produce a summary indicating how many tasks completed, how many were force-cancelled, and how long the shutdown took.\n- Calling shutdown multiple times should be safe and return the same result.\n- If no tasks are processing, shutdown should complete immediately.\n```\n\n---\n\n## Configuration Files\n\n### package.json\n**File: /workspace/package.json**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"bench-task-queue\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Task queue marathon benchmark\",\n  \"type\": \"module\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"build\": \"tsc\",\n    \"lint\": \"eslint src/\",\n    \"test\": \"vitest run\"\n  },\n  \"devDependencies\": {\n    \"@types/node\": \"^25.2.3\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/parser\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"eslint\": \"^8.56.0\",\n    \"typescript\": \"^5.4.0\",\n    \"@vitest/coverage-v8\": \"^2.0.0\",\n    \"vitest\": \"^2.0.0\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### tsconfig.json\n**File: /workspace/tsconfig.json**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"target\": \"ES2022\",\n    \"module\": \"Node16\",\n    \"moduleResolution\": \"Node16\",\n    \"outDir\": \"./dist\",\n    \"rootDir\": \"./src\",\n    \"strict\": true,\n    \"esModuleInterop\": true,\n    \"skipLibCheck\": true,\n    \"forceConsistentCasingInFileNames\": true,\n    \"resolveJsonModule\": true,\n    \"declaration\": true,\n    \"declarationMap\": true,\n    \"sourceMap\": true\n  },\n  \"include\": [\"src/**/*\"],\n  \"exclude\": [\"node_modules\", \"dist\", \"tests\"]\n}\n```\n\n### .eslintrc.cjs\n**File: /workspace/.eslintrc.cjs**\n\n```javascript\nmodule.exports = {\n  parser: '@typescript-eslint/parser',\n  plugins: ['@typescript-eslint'],\n  extends: ['eslint:recommended', 'plugin:@typescript-eslint/recommended'],\n  parserOptions: {\n    ecmaVersion: 2022,\n    sourceType: 'module',\n  },\n  rules: {\n    '@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars': ['error', { argsIgnorePattern: '^_', varsIgnorePattern: '^_' }],\n  },\n  env: {\n    node: true,\n    es2022: true,\n  },\n};\n```\n\n### vitest.config.ts\n**File: /workspace/vitest.config.ts**\n\n```typescript\nimport { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  test: {\n    globals: true,\n    testTimeout: 10000,\n  },\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Project:** A progressive task queue system implementation in TypeScript\n- **Entry point:** `src/index.ts` (to be created)\n- **Build tool:** TypeScript 5.4\n- **Test framework:** Vitest 2.0\n- **Linter:** ESLint with TypeScript support\n- **Node target:** ES2022 with Node16 module resolution\n- **No external runtime dependencies** (only dev tools)\n\nThe project requires implementing 12 phases of increasingly complex task queue features, starting from basic FIFO operations and progressing to advanced features like middleware, recurring tasks, dependencies, and graceful shutdown. The src/ directory is currently empty and ready for implementation."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ae12262 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 20480\ntool_uses: 21\nduration_ms: 43159</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3ccc1ea1-daac-4bb2-8b68-95565e689b6d","uuid":"622fe90c-ab1d-4832-ae16-3e0e45bc1c6b","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need a comprehensive understanding of this task queue project. Please:\n\n1. Read ALL files in the phases/ directory (phases/01.md through phases/12.md) and provide their COMPLETE contents\n2. Read package.json to understand build/test/lint setup\n3. Read tsconfig.json\n4. Check what's in src/ directory if anything exists\n5. Read any eslint/prettier config files\n6. List the overall directory structure\n\nI need the FULL text of every phase file - do not summarize, I need exact requirements.","agentId":"ae12262","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now let me provide you with a comprehensive summary of the project:\n\n## Comprehensive Task Queue Project Overview\n\n### Directory Structure\n\n```\n/workspace/\n├── .eslintrc.cjs                 # ESLint configuration\n├── .gitignore\n├── .thunderdome/                 # Benchmarking/testing framework\n│   └── rubric.yaml\n├── TASK.md                       # Main project overview\n├── package.json                  # Project dependencies and scripts\n├── tsconfig.json                 # TypeScript configuration\n├── vitest.config.ts             # Vitest test runner configuration\n├── phases/                       # 12 phase requirements\n│   ├── phase-01.md\n│   ├── phase-02.md\n│   ├── phase-03.md\n│   ├── phase-04.md\n│   ├── phase-05.md\n│   ├── phase-06.md\n│   ├── phase-07.md\n│   ├── phase-08.md\n│   ├── phase-09.md\n│   ├── phase-10.md\n│   ├── phase-11.md\n│   └── phase-12.md\n├── src/                          # Implementation directory (empty, contains only .gitkeep)\n└── dist/                         # Will be compiled output\n```\n\n---\n\n## All Phase Files - COMPLETE CONTENTS\n\n### Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-01.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n\nImplement the core of the task queue: the ability to add tasks and retrieve them in first-in, first-out order.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- The queue should accept a payload (any data) when a task is added, and return a task object.\n- Each task must have a unique identifier (e.g., UUID), a status, and a creation timestamp.\n- New tasks start in a \"pending\" state.\n- Retrieving the next task should return the oldest pending task and transition it to a \"processing\" state.\n- If no tasks are available, retrieval should return `null`.\n- There should be a way to check how many tasks are waiting.\n```\n\n### Phase 2: Named Queues\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-02.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 2: Named Queues\n\nExtend the system to support multiple independent queues, each identified by a name.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks are added to a specific named queue. If no name is given, a default queue is used.\n- Each named queue operates independently -- adding to one does not affect another.\n- Retrieving a task pulls from the specified queue only.\n- Creating a queue happens implicitly when a task is first added to it.\n- There should be a way to list all queue names that exist.\n- Asking for a task from a non-existent or empty queue returns `null`.\n- The API should remain backward-compatible with Phase 1 (omitting the queue name uses the default).\n```\n\n### Phase 3: Priority\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-03.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 3: Priority\n\nAdd priority support so that more urgent tasks are processed before less urgent ones.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Tasks can be assigned a priority level from 1 (highest) to 10 (lowest). The default priority is 5.\n- When retrieving the next task, higher-priority tasks (lower number) are returned first.\n- Tasks with the same priority are returned in FIFO order.\n- Invalid priority values (outside 1-10) should cause an error.\n- Priority operates per-queue -- each named queue maintains its own priority ordering.\n- The task object should expose its priority level.\n```\n\n### Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-04.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to defer tasks so they only become available for processing after a specified time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A task can be given a delay (in milliseconds) or a specific future time at which it becomes available.\n- Delayed tasks are added to the queue immediately but are not returned when retrieving until their availability time has passed.\n- Non-delayed tasks are always preferred over delayed tasks that are not yet available.\n- When multiple delayed tasks become available simultaneously, they should be ordered by availability time, then priority, then FIFO.\n- The task object should indicate when it becomes available.\n- Delays work correctly with named queues.\n```\n\n### Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-05.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n\nAdd automatic retry functionality so that failed tasks can be re-attempted with increasing delays.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- There should be a way to mark a processing task as completed or failed.\n- When a task fails and has retries remaining, it is automatically re-added to the queue with a delay.\n- The delay follows exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...).\n- The default maximum number of retries is 3, but this should be configurable per task.\n- The base backoff delay defaults to 1000ms but should be configurable per task.\n- The task should track how many times it has been attempted.\n- Retried tasks keep their original queue and priority.\n- If all retries are exhausted, the task remains in a failed state.\n```\n\n### Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-06.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n\nAdd a dead letter queue (DLQ) to capture tasks that have permanently failed after exhausting all retries.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When a task has no more retries left, it is automatically moved to a dead letter queue associated with its original queue.\n- There should be a way to view all dead-lettered tasks for a given queue.\n- Dead-lettered tasks should retain their error information and a count of how many times they failed.\n- It should be possible to move a dead-lettered task back to its original queue for a fresh round of retries.\n- There should be a way to clear all dead-lettered tasks for a queue.\n- Each named queue has its own independent dead letter queue.\n```\n\n### Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-07.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n\nAdd the ability for tasks to declare dependencies on other tasks, so they only become available once their prerequisites are done.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- When adding a task, you can specify a list of task IDs that must complete before this task becomes available.\n- A task with unresolved dependencies is blocked and will not be returned when retrieving.\n- When a dependency completes, the system should check whether any blocked tasks are now unblocked.\n- Circular dependencies (direct or indirect) must be detected and rejected at task-creation time.\n- Depending on a non-existent task should cause an error.\n- A failed dependency does NOT automatically fail its dependents -- they remain blocked.\n- There should be a way to inspect a task's dependency status.\n```\n\n### Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-08.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n\nAdd per-queue limits on how many tasks can be processed at the same time.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Each queue can have a maximum concurrency setting that limits how many tasks can be in a processing state simultaneously.\n- If the concurrency limit is reached, retrieving a task returns `null` even if pending tasks are available.\n- Completing or failing a task frees up a concurrency slot.\n- By default, queues have no concurrency limit (unlimited).\n- There should be a way to set and query the concurrency limit and current active count for a queue.\n- Concurrency interacts correctly with priority ordering -- the highest-priority available task is still chosen, subject to the concurrency limit.\n```\n\n### Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-09.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n\nAdd the ability to report progress on running tasks and to cancel tasks.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A processing task can report its progress as a percentage (0-100) with an optional message.\n- There should be a way to query a task's current progress.\n- Listeners can subscribe to progress updates for a task and receive notifications when progress changes.\n- Subscriptions should be cancellable (unsubscribe).\n- Tasks in pending or processing state can be cancelled.\n- Cancelled pending tasks are removed from the queue and will not be returned.\n- Cancelled processing tasks have their status updated accordingly.\n- Cancelled tasks are never retried, even if they had retries remaining.\n```\n\n### Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-10.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n\nAdd the ability to schedule tasks that recur on a regular interval using simple cron-like expressions.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A schedule associates a cron expression with a queue and a task template (the payload to use each time).\n- Support a simple subset of cron expressions:\n  - `*/N * * * *` -- every N minutes\n  - `0 * * * *` -- every hour on the hour\n  - `0 0 * * *` -- every day at midnight\n- There should be a way to create, remove, and list active schedules.\n- A manual \"tick\" or \"check\" mechanism should evaluate all active schedules and enqueue tasks for any that are due. This is used for testing.\n- Once enqueued, recurring tasks are regular tasks subject to all other queue rules.\n- Removing a schedule stops future occurrences from being created.\n```\n\n### Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-11.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n\nAdd a middleware system that can intercept and transform tasks as they are processed.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Middleware functions can be registered per queue.\n- When a task is processed, it passes through all registered middleware in order before reaching the final handler.\n- Each middleware receives the task and a \"next\" function. Calling \"next\" passes control to the next middleware (or the handler).\n- If a middleware does NOT call \"next\", the task processing is skipped.\n- Middleware can modify the task (e.g., adding metadata or transforming the payload).\n- If a middleware throws an error, the task should be marked as failed.\n- A processing function/handler can be registered per queue. It is invoked after all middleware have run.\n- Each queue has its own independent middleware stack.\n```\n\n### Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n**File: /workspace/phases/phase-12.md**\n\n```\n# Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n\nAdd the ability to shut down the task queue system in an orderly fashion.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- A shutdown operation should signal the system to stop accepting new tasks.\n- After shutdown is initiated, attempting to add new tasks should produce an error.\n- The shutdown should wait for all currently-processing tasks to finish, up to a configurable timeout.\n- If processing tasks do not complete within the timeout, they should be force-cancelled.\n- Callbacks can be registered to run during the shutdown process.\n- The shutdown should produce a summary indicating how many tasks completed, how many were force-cancelled, and how long the shutdown took.\n- Calling shutdown multiple times should be safe and return the same result.\n- If no tasks are processing, shutdown should complete immediately.\n```\n\n---\n\n## Configuration Files\n\n### package.json\n**File: /workspace/package.json**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"bench-task-queue\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Task queue marathon benchmark\",\n  \"type\": \"module\",\n  \"scripts\": {\n    \"build\": \"tsc\",\n    \"lint\": \"eslint src/\",\n    \"test\": \"vitest run\"\n  },\n  \"devDependencies\": {\n    \"@types/node\": \"^25.2.3\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"@typescript-eslint/parser\": \"^7.0.0\",\n    \"eslint\": \"^8.56.0\",\n    \"typescript\": \"^5.4.0\",\n    \"@vitest/coverage-v8\": \"^2.0.0\",\n    \"vitest\": \"^2.0.0\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### tsconfig.json\n**File: /workspace/tsconfig.json**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"target\": \"ES2022\",\n    \"module\": \"Node16\",\n    \"moduleResolution\": \"Node16\",\n    \"outDir\": \"./dist\",\n    \"rootDir\": \"./src\",\n    \"strict\": true,\n    \"esModuleInterop\": true,\n    \"skipLibCheck\": true,\n    \"forceConsistentCasingInFileNames\": true,\n    \"resolveJsonModule\": true,\n    \"declaration\": true,\n    \"declarationMap\": true,\n    \"sourceMap\": true\n  },\n  \"include\": [\"src/**/*\"],\n  \"exclude\": [\"node_modules\", \"dist\", \"tests\"]\n}\n```\n\n### .eslintrc.cjs\n**File: /workspace/.eslintrc.cjs**\n\n```javascript\nmodule.exports = {\n  parser: '@typescript-eslint/parser',\n  plugins: ['@typescript-eslint'],\n  extends: ['eslint:recommended', 'plugin:@typescript-eslint/recommended'],\n  parserOptions: {\n    ecmaVersion: 2022,\n    sourceType: 'module',\n  },\n  rules: {\n    '@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars': ['error', { argsIgnorePattern: '^_', varsIgnorePattern: '^_' }],\n  },\n  env: {\n    node: true,\n    es2022: true,\n  },\n};\n```\n\n### vitest.config.ts\n**File: /workspace/vitest.config.ts**\n\n```typescript\nimport { defineConfig } from 'vitest/config';\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  test: {\n    globals: true,\n    testTimeout: 10000,\n  },\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Project:** A progressive task queue system 